# Research report: What is the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide for glycemic control and weight loss in adults with type 2 diabetes?

### Efficacy

This trial also reported that 82% to 86% of participants receiving tirzepatide achieved an HbA1c of less than 7.0% at 40 weeks, compared to 79% with semaglutide.[1] In the SURPASS-3 trial, a 52-week, open-label, active-controlled study comparing tirzepatide to insulin degludec in patients on metformin with or without an SGLT2 inhibitor, HbA1c reductions were ‚àí1.93%, ‚àí2.20%, and ‚àí2.37% for tirzepatide 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg, respectively, versus ‚àí1.34% with insulin degludec.[2][3] A pre-planned exploratory analysis of SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3 found that the median time to achieve an HbA1c of less than 7.0% was faster with tirzepatide (8.1 weeks for each dose) than with semaglutide 1 mg (12.0 weeks) or insulin degludec (12.1 weeks).[4] In the SURPASS-4 trial, which enrolled patients with type 2 diabetes and increased cardiovascular risk, tirzepatide 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg reduced HbA1c by ‚àí2.24%, ‚àí2.43%, and ‚àí2.58%, respectively, over 52 weeks, compared to a reduction of ‚àí1.44% with insulin glargine.[2][5] In the SURPASS-AP-Combo trial conducted in the Asia-Pacific region, all tirzepatide doses were superior to insulin glargine, with HbA1c reductions of ‚àí2.24%, ‚àí2.44%, and ‚àí2.49% for the 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg doses, respectively, versus ‚àí0.95% with insulin glargine at 40 weeks.[2][6]

### Safety

Gastrointestinal adverse events are the most common safety concern with tirzepatide, occurring in a dose-dependent manner.[7] Another systematic review noted that compared to the 5 mg dose, tirzepatide 10 mg and 15 mg were associated with more frequent nausea (P<0.001) and vomiting (P=0.007 for 5 mg vs. 10 mg; P<0.001 for 5 mg vs. 15 mg).[8][9] These events often led to treatment discontinuation; one analysis found drug discontinuation due to adverse events was highest with the 15 mg dose at 10%, and another systematic review reported higher discontinuation rates with tirzepatide 10 mg (pooled RR=1.75) and 15 mg (pooled RR=2.03) compared to GLP-1 receptor agonists.[7][8][9] In the obesity trial SURMOUNT-4, during the initial open-label lead-in period with tirzepatide, 35.5% of participants experienced nausea, 21.1% diarrhea, 20.7% constipation, and 16.3% vomiting.[10][11] In SURPASS-AP-Combo, where tirzepatide was compared to insulin glargine, no severe hypoglycemia was reported.[6] A meta-analysis found the incidence of mild hypoglycemia (blood glucose <70 mg/dL) was highest with the tirzepatide 10 mg dose at 22.6% (95% CI, 9.2%-39.8%).[7] However, another systematic review concluded the overall safety profile was similar to GLP-1 receptor agonists except for a higher risk of hypoglycemia with the 15 mg dose (pooled RR=3.83, 95% CI 1.19-12.30) and higher discontinuation rates.[8][9] A meta-analysis found rates of MTC and other serious events like acute pancreatitis and cholecystitis were ‚â§1% across all tirzepatide doses.[7] In the SURMOUNT-CN obesity trial, one case of papillary thyroid cancer occurred in a participant with a history of thyroid nodules receiving tirzepatide 15 mg, which was considered unrelated to treatment by the investigator, and no cases of medullary thyroid cancer were reported.[12] Similarly, in the SURMOUNT-4 trial, no cases of medullary thyroid carcinoma were reported.[10][11] A real-world pharmacovigilance analysis identified a signal for medullary thyroid carcinoma with an EB05 of 3.55, based on 3 reported cases.[13] Other adverse events of interest include pancreatitis, with the same pharmacovigilance analysis reporting 190 cases and a signal strength (EB05=6.85), though adjudicated confirmed cases in trials were low; for example, SURMOUNT-4 reported no adjudication-confirmed cases of pancreatitis.[13][10][11] Gallbladder-related events such as cholelithiasis and acute cholecystitis have also been reported at low frequencies.[10][11][12][7]

### Comparative

A systematic review and network meta-analysis of subcutaneous GLP-1 receptor agonists and tirzepatide concluded that all three tirzepatide doses were comparable to semaglutide 2.0 mg and superior to semaglutide 1.0 mg and 0.5 mg in reducing HbA1c, while demonstrating greater weight loss than the corresponding semaglutide doses.[14] A post hoc analysis of SURPASS-2 found tirzepatide increased the odds of achieving composite therapeutic targets, such as HbA1c <7.0% with weight loss >10%, compared to semaglutide 1 mg.[15] For weight loss specifically in populations with overweight or obesity, a meta-analysis of direct comparative studies reported a standardized mean difference of 0.75 favoring tirzepatide over semaglutide, and a real-world evidence study in a US cohort with overweight or obesity reported patients on tirzepatide had significantly higher rates of achieving ‚â•5%, ‚â•10%, and ‚â•15% weight loss within one year.[16][17] In SURPASS-3 versus insulin degludec, tirzepatide 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg produced greater HbA1c reductions and body weight reductions ranging from -7.5 kg to -12.9 kg, whereas insulin degludec was associated with weight gain of +2.3 kg.[3] Similarly, in SURPASS-4 versus insulin glargine in patients at increased cardiovascular risk, all tirzepatide doses provided superior HbA1c reductions and weight reductions between -6.4 kg and -10.6 kg, compared to weight gain of +1.9 kg with insulin glargine.[5] Another systematic review and meta-analysis confirmed these findings, reporting tirzepatide was associated with significantly greater proportions of patients achieving HbA1c targets of <7.0% (80-89% vs. 49%) and weight loss ‚â•5% (62-83% vs. 7%) compared to long-acting insulin.[18] A network meta-analysis in patients on basal insulin background therapy found tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg provided statistically significant greater reductions in HbA1c and body weight versus GLP-1 receptor agonists dulaglutide, exenatide, and lixisenatide.[19] The indirect comparison versus semaglutide 2 mg reported a similar overall safety profile, though tirzepatide 10 mg and 15 mg had higher odds of treatment discontinuation due to adverse events.[20] Compared to basal insulin, tirzepatide is associated with more gastrointestinal adverse events but a significantly lower risk of hypoglycemia.[21][18]

### Dose Response

Tirzepatide demonstrates dose-dependent improvements in both glycemic control and body weight reduction across its 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg doses in patients with type 2 diabetes.[2][22][23] Similarly, for weight loss, the same meta-analysis found that compared to tirzepatide 5 mg, the 10 mg dose reduced body weight by an additional 2.64 kg and the 15 mg dose by an additional 4.26 kg.[23] This pattern is evident in individual trials; in SURPASS-3, weight reductions at 52 weeks were ‚àí7.5 kg, ‚àí10.7 kg, and ‚àí12.9 kg for the 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg doses, respectively, compared to a 2.3 kg increase with insulin degludec.[2][3] In SURPASS-4, weight changes were ‚àí7.1 kg, ‚àí9.5 kg, and ‚àí11.7 kg for the three doses versus a 1.9 kg increase with insulin glargine.[2][5] The proportion of patients achieving clinically meaningful weight loss thresholds also increases with dose.[2] The time to achieve treatment targets is also dose-influenced, with higher doses leading to faster responses.[4] A pre-planned analysis of SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3 found that the median time to first achieve an HbA1c <7.0% was 8.1 weeks for all tirzepatide doses, compared to 12.0 weeks for semaglutide 1 mg and 12.1 weeks for insulin degludec.[4] For weight loss, the median time to achieve ‚â•5% body weight reduction in SURPASS-2 was 16.0 weeks with tirzepatide 5 mg and 12.4 weeks with the 10 mg and 15 mg doses, versus 24.0 weeks with semaglutide 1 mg.[4] While efficacy increases with dose, so does the incidence of gastrointestinal adverse events, though serious adverse event rates are generally similar across doses.[22][23] One meta-analysis reports that the risk of total adverse events was significantly higher with tirzepatide 10 mg (risk ratio 1.20) and 15 mg (risk ratio 1.26) compared to the 5 mg dose.[23] Another analysis concluded that tirzepatide 5 mg had the best safety profile among the three doses, while the 15 mg dose provided the greatest efficacy benefit for glycemic and weight control.[22] For optimal long-term weight maintenance, continued treatment with the maximum tolerated dose (10 mg or 15 mg) is necessary, as evidenced by the SURMOUNT-4 trial where switching to placebo after 36 weeks of tirzepatide led to a 14.0% weight regain, while continued treatment yielded an additional 5.5% reduction.[11]

### Regulatory

Tirzepatide is approved by the FDA under the proprietary name Mounjaro as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus.[24] The FDA-approved dosing regimen starts at 2.5 mg subcutaneously once weekly, with increases in 2.5 mg increments after a minimum of 4 weeks on the current dose, up to a maximum of 15 mg once weekly.[24][25] The European Medicines Agency (EMA) authorizes tirzepatide (Mounjaro) for the same T2DM indication in adults, as monotherapy when metformin is inappropriate or as an add-on to other antidiabetic medicines.[26][27] The EMA also approves tirzepatide for weight management as an adjunct to a reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity in adults with an initial BMI of ‚â•30 kg/m¬≤ (obesity) or ‚â•27 kg/m¬≤ to <30 kg/m¬≤ (overweight) in the presence of at least one weight-related comorbidity.[28][26] For the chronic weight management indication, the FDA approved tirzepatide under the name Zepbound, with an identical starting and titration schedule up to 15 mg once weekly.[29][30] A key safety warning from both agencies is a boxed warning for risk of thyroid C-cell tumors, as tirzepatide caused thyroid C-cell tumors in rats, though human relevance is unknown.[31][32] Consequently, tirzepatide is contraindicated in patients with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) or in patients with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2 (MEN 2).[31][32] Other warnings and precautions common to the labels include the risk of severe gastrointestinal adverse reactions, acute pancreatitis, hypoglycemia with concomitant insulin secretagogues or insulin, hypersensitivity reactions, acute kidney injury, acute gallbladder disease, and potential impact on absorption of oral medications due to delayed gastric emptying.[31][32] The EMA product information additionally notes a mean increase in heart rate and includes diabetic retinopathy complications and pulmonary aspiration during anesthesia as precautions.[26] The UK's National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) recommends tirzepatide for treating T2DM in adults only under specific conditions: when triple therapy with metformin and two other oral antidiabetic drugs is ineffective, not tolerated, or contraindicated, and the patient has a BMI of 35 kg/m¬≤ or more with associated psychological or medical problems, or a BMI under 35 kg/m¬≤ where insulin therapy has significant occupational implications or weight loss would benefit other obesity-related complications.[33][34] NICE guidance also specifies using lower BMI thresholds for people from certain ethnic backgrounds.[33] For weight management, NICE provides a prescribing guide, confirming the starting dose of 2.5 mg once weekly and titration by 2.5 mg every 4 weeks to recommended maintenance doses of 5 mg, 10 mg, or 15 mg once weekly.[35]

### Limitations

Limitations: The evidence base is heavily weighted towards lower-tier sources, with only 14% of sources being T1 primary studies and 33% classified as T4 narrative reviews. The pipeline detected 13 high-severity contradictions, primarily concerning tirzepatide's effect on body weight and weight loss, where sources disagree substantially on the magnitude of the reported outcomes. The analyzed evidence spans from 2010 to the present, which may not capture the full historical context of earlier therapeutic approaches. The low proportion of high-tier evidence (T1-T3 combined at 39%) suggests conclusions are often supported by secondary or summary literature.

