comparison used 1 mg, not the 2 mg dose now available for type 2 diabetes. Patients with prior
pancreatitis, severe gastrointestinal disease, advanced retinopathy requiring treatment, and more
advanced kidney disease were often absent from the pivotal populations. Most eÔ¨Écacy trials were 40 to 52
weeks, and although SURPASS-4 and CVOT extend the horizon, the long-term safety practicalities of
sustained high-dose therapy in real-world multimorbidity still need reÔ¨Ånement. These are genuine evidence
gaps, not just theoretical caveats. 
The development program is also still moving. SURPASS-CVOT has now reported, materially strengthening
cardiovascular safety assessment. Switch studies are becoming important because many patients are now
already taking a GLP-1 receptor agonist before tirzepatide is considered. SURPASS-SWITCH, reported in
2026, found that switching from dulaglutide to tirzepatide produced greater glycemic and weight
improvements than escalating dulaglutide. ClinicalTrials.gov also lists ongoing or recently active adult type
2 diabetes studies evaluating investigational tirzepatide doses, tirzepatide in adults with type 2 diabetes
and overweight or obesity, and switch strategies from prior GLP-1 receptor agonist therapy to tirzepatide.
Those studies should improve the evidence base for sequencing and for dose optimization beyond the
original pivotal program. 
