Taken together, the evidence supports a clear conclusion: tirzepatide is one of the most eÔ¨Äective available
agents for combined glycemic control and weight reduction in adults with type 2 diabetes, with a beneÔ¨Åt
proÔ¨Åle that is quantitatively large, durable, and consistent across treatment stages. Its main limitation is not
lack of eÔ¨Écacy but tolerability and selection: the right patient can beneÔ¨Åt a great deal, while the wrong
patient may stop because of gastrointestinal symptoms or may need a diÔ¨Äerent agent because of comorbid
risk. For clinicians, the practical task is therefore less ‚Äúdoes tirzepatide work?‚Äù and more ‚Äúwhich adults with
type 2 diabetes stand to gain more from its metabolic potency than they risk from its tolerability burden?‚Äù
The SURPASS program makes that tradeoÔ¨Ä much easier to judge than it was a few years ago. 
